metatags.og:title: With weaker mandate, Rutte must choose his compromises to form a government
metatags.og:description: By Anthony Deutsch and Thomas Escritt  AMSTERDAM (Reuters) - After fending off nationalist Geert Wilders at Monday's election, Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte must patch together a stable coalition that reflects the rise of fringe parties that made huge gains on the left and right.  The process cannot formally begin until Rutte's VVD has been asked to head formation talks and preliminary election results have been declared official by the Electoral Council on Tuesday, and could take weeks or months.  Talks could drag on until after the summer as parties dig in their heels on their policy red lines, according to NRC newspaper commentator Tom-Jan Meeus.
